Project: An investigation into an Appontment dataset¶

Table of Contents¶

  • Introduction
  • Data Wrangling
  • Data Cleaning
  • Exploratory Data Analysis
  • Conclusions

Introduction¶

For this project I have chosen to look at an appointment dataset. This data was provided as part of the Udacity Data Analysis Nanodegree and was originally found at Kaggle.

Question:

What factors have the biggest impact on whether a patient will show up for their appointment?

General Properties¶

Get things setup to work with the data

In [3]:

Data Wrangling¶

Now to begin getting the data into a useful fashion.

Change the data type for some items to more logiccally be bool type.

In [7]:
appts[['Scholarship','Hipertension','Diabetes','Alcoholism','Handcap','SMS_received']] = appts[['Scholarship','Hipertension','Diabetes','Alcoholism','Handcap','SMS_received']].astype('bool')

Going to change the datatypes for the dates and times for scheduled and actual appointments.

In [8]:
appts['ScheduledDay'] = pd.to_datetime(appts['ScheduledDay']) #this line converts the ScheduledDay to a datetime type
appts['AppointmentDay'] = pd.to_datetime(appts['AppointmentDay']) #same as above, just for the appointment day

Now looking at the output data from the value_counts method, even though Age 0 was looking a bit odd, it occurse frequently. This is likely not a mistake then, and reflects an unborn child by my logic. The other Ages that cause me to ponder are the ages over 100. However, there are multiple entries for that age range, so it does not seem to be misentered data. I will check those entries to see if they are all the same patient at each age in a moment. The age of -1 will need to be checked, as there is only the single entry which suggests it might have been a misentry of the data.

appts_that_showed = appts.copy() #create a copy of the data to look at it and drop uneeded catigories
did_not_show_up_appts = appts.copy() #second copy that I will be testing 
appts_that_showed.drop(['AppointmentID', 'ScheduledDay', 'AppointmentDay'], axis=1, inplace=True)
did_not_show_up_appts.drop(['AppointmentID', 'ScheduledDay', 'AppointmentDay'], axis=1, inplace=True)
appts_that_showed.drop(appts[appts['No-show'] == 'No'].index, inplace = True) #removing the no-show rows so I will just see those that DID NOT show up
did_not_show_up_appts.drop(appts[appts['No-show'] == 'Yes'].index, inplace = True)

Exploratory Data Analysis¶

Now to begin exploring the data!

Grab the first columns to be checked, which will be the Gender column.

In [26]:
per_gender_F = appts_that_showed[appts_that_showed['Gender'] == 'F']
F_count = len(per_gender_F.index)
per_gender_M = appts_that_showed[appts_that_showed['Gender'] == 'M']
M_count = len(per_gender_M.index)
index = appts_that_showed.index
showing_up_count = len(index)
F_results = '{0:.1%}'.format(1.0* F_count / showing_up_count)
print'The percentage of women that showed up for their appointment was:', F_results
M_results = '{0:.1%}'.format(1.0* M_count / showing_up_count)
print'The percentage of men that showed up for their appointment was:', M_results

The percentage of women that showed up for their appointment was: 65.4%
The percentage of men that showed up for their appointment was: 34.6%

Conclusion¶

In summary, although there are still limitations in the data (for example, in the category of 'No-Show' I take it to mean that a person did not show up for their appointment when the value is "True" but this could be in error.) and also limitations in the analysis. However, based on observations, some insights can be gained that can be useful.

From looking over the data, what is observed is a few interesting finds that might prove useful to a buisness and helping patients keep their appointments. These are as follows:

-A majority of all patients are female, with both sexes keeping their appointments approximately the same amount of times.

-A patient with a handicap is only 18.7% likely to keep their appointment.

-Alcoholics will keep their appointments 20.1% of the time.

-Diabetics will show up for appointments 18% of the time.

-Hipertension is the lowest, only keeping appointments 17.3% of the time.

-Sholarships are the second highest, keeping their appointments 23.7%.

-And receiving a SMS reminder will have patients keep their appointment 27.6% of the time.

-Neighbourhood does not have a signigicant affect on clients keeping their appointments.

-And the age that is mostly seen based on the data is children under the age of 2.

These are the biggest factors that impact whether a patient will show up for their appointment.
